# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: salesforce-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Founded by former Oracle executive Marc Benioff in March 1999, Salesforce grew quickly, making its initial public offering in 2004.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Its major acquisitions included Tableau and Slack.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] As of March 2026, Salesforce has a market capitalization of approximately US$186 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] For fiscal year 2026 (ending January 31, 2026), the company reported record annual revenue of $41.5 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The company is a component of the Dow Jones Industrial Average (since 2020) and the S&P 500.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce was founded on March 8, 1999, by former Oracle executive Marc Benioff, together with Parker Harris, Dave Moellenhoff, and Frank Dominguez as a software-as-a-service (SaaS) company.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The first prototype of Salesforce was launched in November 1999.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Two of Salesforce's earliest investors were Larry Ellison, the co-founder and first CEO of Oracle, and Halsey Minor, the founder of CNET.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce was severely affected by the dot-com bubble bursting at the beginning of the new millennium, resulting in the company laying off 20% of its workforce.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Despite its losses, Salesforce held up during the early 2000s.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce also gained notability during this period for its "the end of software" tagline and marketing campaign, and even hired actors to hold up signs with its slogan outside a Siebel Systems conference.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce's revenue continued to increase, moving from $5.4 million in 2000 to $22.4 million in 2001.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2003, Salesforce held its first annual Dreamforce conference in San Francisco.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] There were around 1,300 attendees and 50 exhibitors at the conference.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In June 2004, the company had its initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange (under the stock symbol CRM) and raised US$110 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2006, Salesforce launched Idea Exchange, a platform that allows customers to connect with company product managers.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2009, Salesforce passed $1 billion in annual revenue.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Also, in 2009, the company launched Service Cloud, an application that helps companies manage service conversations about their products and services.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2014, the company released Trailhead, a free online learning platform for its products.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In October 2014, Salesforce announced the development of its Customer Success Platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2016, Salesforce announced the launch of Einstein, an artificial intelligence platform that supports several of Salesforce's cloud services.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce licensed the right to use Albert Einstein's image and likeness from the Einstein Estate under a 20-year agreement for $20 million, restricted to business software applications.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce acquired the visual analytics and business intelligence software platform Tableau in August 2019 for $15.7 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2020, Salesforce joined the Dow Jones Industrial Average, replacing energy giant and Standard Oil-descendant ExxonMobil.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce's ascension to the Dow Jones was concurrent with that of Amgen and Honeywell.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Because the Dow Jones factors its components by market price, Salesforce was the largest technology component of the index at its accession.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce experienced significant leadership transitions between 2020 and 2021; Keith Block stepped down as co-CEO in February 2020, leaving Marc Benioff as sole chairman and CEO.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In February 2021, Weaver, previously the chief legal officer, became CFO, where she served until stepping down in August 2024.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Former CFO Mark Hawkins announced that he would be retiring in October.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In November 2021, Bret Taylor was named vice chair and co-CEO of the company alongside Benioff.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In December 2020, Salesforce announced its acquisition of Slack for $27.7 billion, the largest in company history; the deal closed in July 2021.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The purchase price represented a 54% premium over Slack's closing market capitalization at the announcement date, valued at approximately $18 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce justified the premium based on anticipated synergies from integrating Slack's messaging platform with its CRM services.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce launched the Sustainability Cloud (Net Zero Cloud as of 2022), which is used by companies to track progress towards achieving their net zero emissions goals.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In August 2022, Salesforce surpassed SAP in total revenue and market capitalization to become the world's largest enterprise applications software company, according to industry analysis.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The next month, Salesforce announced a partnership with Meta Platforms.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The deal called for Meta's consumer application WhatsApp to integrate Salesforce's Customer 360 platform to allow consumers to communicate with companies directly.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In November 2022, Salesforce announced it would terminate some employees from its sales team.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] That same month, Salesforce announced its co-CEO and vice chair, Bret Taylor, would be stepping down from his roles at the end of January 2023, with Benioff continuing to run the company and serve as board chair.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Within the week, former Tableau CEO Mark Nelson and former Slack CEO Stewart Butterfield also announced their departures.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] When asked about departures, Benioff stated, "people come and people go." Following these executive transitions, Salesforce's stock declined significantly, with market analysts attributing the decline to concerns about leadership stability and strategic continuity.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In January 2023, the company announced a layoff of about 10%, or approximately 8,000 positions.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] According to Benioff, the company hired too aggressively during the COVID-19 pandemic and the increase in working from home led to the layoff.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The company also reduced office space as part of the restructuring plan.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The same month brought an announcement from activist investor Elliott Management that it would acquire a "big stake" in the company.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In January 2024, Salesforce announced it was laying off 700 of its global staff.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In October 2025, Salesforce CEO Marc Benioff declared his avid support of Donald Trump and urged him to deploy the National Guard to San Francisco as Trump was deploying federal troops to other cities.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The comments generated significant controversy for Benioff and Salesforce, including push-back from San Francisco mayor Daniel Lurie and District Attorney Brooke Jenkins and the resignation of Ron Conway from the Salesforce Foundation board.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Benioff subsequently apologized for his National Guard comments.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] That same month, Salesforce pitched the Trump administration on ways that Salesforce's AI tools could help Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) triple its staff to support the administration's mass deportation campaign.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The company had previously contracted for ICE under the Obama and Biden administrations.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce offers several customer relationship management (CRM) services for enterprises and small businesses, including Sales Cloud, Service Cloud, Marketing Cloud,Commerce Cloud and Platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Additional technologies include Slack.Salesforce also offers a free CRM for small teams of up to two people.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Other services include app creation, data integration and visualization, and training.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce launched a suite of features called Salesforce Foundations in September 2024, bundling connected functionality across department-specific Sales Cloud and Service Cloud products.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Launched at Dreamforce in 2016, Salesforce Einstein was the company's first artificial intelligence product.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2023, Salesforce announced ChatGPT integration in Slack was available to any organization, and the launch of Einstein GPT, a generative AI service.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2024, Salesforce launched Einstein Copilot: Health Actions, an assistant based on its earlier artificial intelligence platform Einstein.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] It can be used to assist in making appointments, referrals, and gathering patient information.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In July, Salesforce released an AI agent with the ability to perform customer service actions, like enabling product returns or refunds.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September and October 2024, the company deployed Agentforce (succeeding Salesforce Einstein), an agentic AI.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] This enables the use of chatbots within its software.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce CEO Marc Benioff said in a June 2025 interview that artificial intelligence performed between 30% and 50% of internal work at Salesforce, including functions such as software engineering, customer service, marketing, and analytics.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce Platform (formerly known as Force.com) is a platform as a service (PaaS) that allows developers to add applications to the main Salesforce.com application.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] These applications are hosted on Salesforce.com infrastructure.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Force.com applications are built using Apex, a proprietary Java-like programming language, to generate HTML originally via the "Visualforce" framework.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Beginning in 2015, the "Lightning Components" framework has been supported.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The Apex language and compiler were initially designed by Craig Weissman.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] As of 2014, the Force.com platform had 1.5 million registered developers according to Salesforce.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Launched in 2005, the Salesforce AppExchange is an online app store that allows users to sell third-party applications and consulting services.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Launched in 2014, Trailhead is a free online learning platform with courses focused on Salesforce technologies.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Desk.com was a SaaS help desk and customer support product acquired by Salesforce for $50 million in 2011, and consolidated with other services into Service Cloud Essentials in March 2018.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Do.com was a cloud-based task management system for small groups and businesses, introduced in 2011, and discontinued in 2014.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2006, Salesforce acquired Sendia, a mobile web service firm, for $15 million and Kieden, an online advertising company.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2007, Koral, a content management service, was acquired.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2008, Salesforce acquired Instranet for $31.5 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2010, Salesforce acquired multiple companies, including Jigsaw, a cloud-based data service provider, for $142 million, Heroku, a Ruby application platform-as-a-service, for $212 million, and Activa Live Chat, a live chat software provider.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2011, Salesforce acquired Dimdim, a web conferencing platform, for $31 million, Radian6, a social media tracking company, for $340 million, and Rypple, a performance management software company.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Rypple became known as Work.com in 2012.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2012, Salesforce acquired Buddy Media, a social media marketer, for $689 million, and GoInstant, a browser collaboration startup, for $70 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2013, Salesforce acquired ExactTarget, an email marketer, for $2.5 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2014, Salesforce acquired RelateIQ, a data company, for $390 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2015, Salesforce acquired multiple companies for undisclosed sums, including Toopher, a mobile authentication company, Tempo, an AI calendar app, and MinHash, an AI platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The company also acquired SteelBrick, a software company, for $360 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2016, Salesforce acquired Demandware, a cloud-based provider of e-commerce services, for $2.8 billion and Quip, a word processing app, for $750 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2017, the company acquired Sequence, a user experience design agency.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2018, Salesforce acquired several companies, including MuleSoft, a cloud service company, for $6.5 billion, as well as Rebel, an email services provider, and Datorama, an AI marketing platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2019, Salesforce completed its acquisition of analytics software company Tableau for $15.7 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce also acquired ClickSoftware for $1.35 billion in 2019.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Slack Technologies was acquired for $27.7 billion in 2021.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce also made smaller acquisitions between 2020 and 2021, including consulting firm Acumen Solutions for $570 million, CRM firm Vlocity for $1.33 billion, privacy compliance startup Phennecs for $16.5 million, and robotic process automation firm Servicetrace.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce's acquired Slack-bot maker Troops.ai in July 2022.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2023, Salesforce acquired Airkit.ai, a creator of AI-powered customer service applications and experiences.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In December 2023, Salesforce acquired Spiff, an automated commission management platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2024, Salesforce acquired data management firm Own for $1.9 billion, and enterprise management platform Zoomin.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce has also acquired PredictSpring and Tenyx in 2024.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In June 2025, Salesforce announced plans to acquire data management platform Informatica for approximately $8 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The deal strengthens Salesforce's data integration and governance capabilities across its platform ecosystem.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Prior negotiations in 2024 failed due to disagreements over valuation and deal structure.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In November 2025, Salesforce announced the successful completion of its acquisition of Informatica for approximately $8 billion in equity value.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The deal was completed ahead of the original early-2026 target.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] By February 2026, Salesforce reported that Informatica had already begun contributing significantly to its financial results, including nearly $400 million in revenue during the fourth quarter of fiscal year 2026.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In June 2026, Salesforce announced the acqusition of Contentful for a reported sum of between $1 billion and $1.5 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In June 2026, Salesforce announced that it had signed a definitive agreement to acquire m3ter, a London-based metering and rating platform for consumption-based billing.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce is headquartered in San Francisco in the Salesforce Tower.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce has 110 offices, including offices in Hong Kong, Tel Aviv, London, Paris, Sydney and Tokyo.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Standard & Poor's added Salesforce to the S&P 500 Index in September 2008.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In August 2020, S&P Dow Jones Indices announced that Salesforce would replace ExxonMobil in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] According to Marc Benioff, Salesforce corporate culture is based on 'Ohana,' a Hawaiian concept emphasizing family and community.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Benioff has described this philosophy as prioritizing employee well-being and broader stakeholder relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2021, Cynthia Perry, a design research senior manager, publicly resigned from Salesforce alleging workplace discrimination related to diversity and inclusion practices and posting her resignation letter on LinkedIn.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] On September 10, 2021, Benioff tweeted that the company is prepared to help any employee who wishes to move out of the state of Texas, following abortion legislation in Texas, announced on September 1, 2021.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce ranked 126th on the 2022 Fortune 500 list of the largest United States companies by revenue.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2008, Salesforce migrated from Sun Fire E25K servers with SPARC processors running Solaris, to Dell servers with AMD processors, running Linux.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2012, Salesforce announced plans to build a data center in the UK to handle European citizens' personal data.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2013, Salesforce and Oracle announced a nine-year partnership focusing on applications, platforms, and infrastructure.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2016, Salesforce announced that it will use Amazon Web Services hosting for countries with restrictive data residency requirements and where no Salesforce data centers are operating.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In November 2007, a phishing attack compromised contact information on a number of Salesforce customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Some customers then received phishing emails that appeared to be invoices from Salesforce.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] A Salesforce employee's credentials were stolen through social engineering.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce stated the incident resulted from human manipulation rather than a software vulnerability in its platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] On April 13, 2022, GitHub notified Heroku of unauthorized access to its systems through a compromised OAuth token.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Heroku immediately revoked all affected tokens and notified customers to update their credentials.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] ShinyHunters has conducted several widespread data theft and extortion campaigns against Salesforce and thousands of its customers as noted by Google's Threat Intelligence Group/Mandiant, Salesforce, and the FBI.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2017, two Salesforce security engineers were fired after giving a presentation at DEF CON discussing a Salesforce pentesting framework called MEATPISTOL.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] MEATPISTOL was a Salesforce-developed exploit framework similar to (and named after) Metasploit.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The terminated employees called on the company to open-source the software after being dismissed.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2018, the not-for-profit organization Refugee and Immigrant Center for Education and Legal Services (RAICES) rejected a US$250,000 donation from Salesforce, citing the company's contracts to provide technology services to U.S.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] RAICES stated that accepting funds from a company supporting immigration enforcement conflicted with its mission to advocate for immigrant and refugee rights.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] According to an Institute on Taxation and Economic Policy analysis published in December 2019, Salesforce paid no federal income tax on its 2018 profits, achieving a 0% effective tax rate.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The report attributed this to provisions in the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 and available tax credits and deductions.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Their findings were published in a report based on the 379 *Fortune* 500 companies that declared a profit in 2018.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2019, Salesforce faced a lawsuit by 50 anonymous women claiming to be victims and survivors of sex trafficking, abuse, and rape, alleging the company profited from and helped build technology that facilitated sex trafficking on the now-defunct Backpage.com.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2021, a judge granted partial dismissal of the case, dismissing charges of negligence and conspiracy, but allowed the case to proceed regarding charges of sex trafficking.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2024, the case was dismissed without prejudice, meaning the plaintiffs could potentially refile their claims in the future.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2024, the US Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit denied a motion to reverse the dismissal.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In July 2021, a former Salesforce Japan employee sued the company in Tokyo District Court, alleging discrimination based on disabilities (autism and ADHD), including denial of reasonable workplace accommodations.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] At that time, Japanese law required private companies to employ at least 2.3% disabled employees or pay a mandatory levy.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Salesforce Japan reportedly failed to meet this threshold from 2009 to 2021 (except in 2017) and did not report the number of disabled employees to labor officials in 2020.[174] The firm declined to comment on the suit to the media.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The ex-employee, who is autistic with ADHD, claimed she was discriminated against because of her disability and was terminated from the firm's Japanese web marketing team.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The suit alleged that the anonymous woman, as an employee at Salesforce Japan from 2018 to 2020, faced hate speech, microaggressions, and rejection of reasonable accommodation from the manager.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] She alleged that her attempts to resolve the problem were met with pressure from HR and a job coach.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] As of 2026, no public record of a resolution to this case has been reported.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In January 2023, Salesforce reported that 8,000 employees had been laid off as a result of over-hiring during the COVID-19 lockdowns and a global economic downturn.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2023, the *Wall Street Journal* reported that actor Matthew McConaughey received annual compensation of approximately $10 million as a 'creative advisor and TV pitchman.' The arrangement was disclosed amid scrutiny of executive spending during the company's major 2023 layoffs.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] American musician will.i.am was also cited as being on the company's payroll due to his "strong understanding of technology".
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2024, former Salesforce Senior Director Dina Zelikson filed a lawsuit against the company in San Francisco Superior Court, alleging wrongful termination, discrimination, and retaliation during a medical leave.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2025, Benioff drew criticism after announcing that Salesforce had eliminated approximately 4,000 customer service roles following the deployment of AI-powered support agents.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The decision contrasted with Benioff's earlier remarks suggesting that artificial intelligence would augment, rather than replace, white-collar workers.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In February 2026, Salesforce initiated a new round of layoffs affecting approximately 1,000 employees across its marketing, product management, and data analytics departments.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The cuts reportedly included staff from the Agentforce AI product team, the department responsible for the company's pivot to autonomous agents.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] During Salesforce's annual company kickoff in February 2026, CEO Marc Benioff made a series of jokes regarding U.S.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE).
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The comments caused widespread outrage on internal Slack channels, with employees circulating a letter demanding the company denounce ICE and halt the sale of Agentforce infrastructure to the agency.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] The incident led to a public rebuke from co-founder Parker Harris, who stated he was "not OK" with the remarks.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In March 2026, company president Robin Washington held a town hall to address "internal tensions" and the resulting leaks to the press regarding the incident.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2009, Salesforce began investing in startups.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] These investments became Salesforce Ventures, headed by John Somorjai.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In September 2014, SFV set up Salesforce1 Fund, aimed at start-ups creating applications primarily for mobile phones.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In December 2018, Salesforce Ventures announced the launch of the Japan Trailblazer Fund, focused on Japanese startups.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In August 2018, Salesforce Ventures reported investments totaling over $1 billion in 275 companies, including CloudCraze (e-commerce), Figure Eight (artificial intelligence), Forter (online fraud prevention), and FinancialForce (automation software).
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2019, SFV's five largest investments—Domo (data-visualization software), SurveyMonkey (online survey software), Twilio (cloud-communication), Dropbox (cloud storage), and DocuSign (secure e-signature company)—accounted for nearly half of its portfolio.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In 2021, Salesforce announced that its investments had resulted in a $2.17 billion annual gain.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] In June 2023, Salesforce increased the size of its Generative AI Fund for startups from $250 million to $500 million, and in September 2024 to $1 billion.
[src:salesforce-platform/apex-programming-language] To date, Salesforce Ventures has invested $5 billion in companies based in 27 different countries.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems compile data from a range of different communication channels, including a company's website, telephone (which many services come with a softphone), email, live chat, marketing materials, and more recently, social media.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] They allow businesses to learn more about their target audiences and how to better cater to their needs, thus retaining customers and driving sales growth.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM may be used with past, present or potential customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The concepts, procedures, and rules that a corporation follows when communicating with its consumers are referred to as CRM.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This complete connection covers direct contact with customers, such as sales and service-related operations, forecasting, and the analysis of consumer patterns and behaviours, from the perspective of the company.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The concept of customer relationship management started in the early 1970s, when customer satisfaction was evaluated using annual surveys or by front-line asking.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] At that time, businesses had to rely on standalone mainframe systems to automate sales, but the extent of technology allowed them to categorize customers in spreadsheets and lists.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] One of the best-known precursors of modern-day CRM is the Farley File.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Developed by Franklin Roosevelt's campaign manager, James Farley, the Farley File was a comprehensive set of records detailing political and personal facts about people FDR and Farley met or were supposed to meet.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Using it, people that FDR met were impressed by his "recall" of facts about their family and what they were doing professionally and politically.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Kestenbaum introduced the concept of database marketing, namely applying statistical methods to analyze and gather customer data.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] By 1987, Pat Sullivan and Mike Muhney had released a customer evaluation system called ACT! based on the principle of a digital Rolodex, which offered a contact management service for the first time.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The trend was followed by numerous companies and independent developers trying to maximize lead potential, including Tom Siebel of Siebel Systems, who designed the first CRM product, Siebel Customer Relationship Management, in 1993.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This included embedding sales force automation or extended customer service (e.g. inquiry, activity management) as CRM features in their ERP.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Customer relationship management was popularized in 1997 due to the work of Siebel, Gartner, and IBM.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Between 1997 and 2000, leading CRM products were enriched with shipping and marketing capabilities.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Siebel introduced the first mobile CRM app called Siebel Sales Handheld in 1999.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The idea of a stand-alone, cloud-hosted customer base was soon adopted by other leading providers at the time, including PeopleSoft (acquired by Oracle), Oracle, SAP and Salesforce.com.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The first open-source CRM system was developed by SugarCRM in 2004.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] During this period, CRM was rapidly migrating to the cloud, as a result of which it became accessible to sole entrepreneurs and small teams.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This increase in accessibility generated a huge wave of price reduction.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Around 2009, developers began considering the options to profit from social media's momentum and designed tools to help companies become accessible on all users' favourite networks.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many startups at the time benefited from this trend to provide exclusively social CRM solutions, including Base and Nutshell.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The same year, Gartner organized and held the first Customer Relationship Management Summit, and summarized the features systems should offer to be classified as CRM solutions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In 2013 and 2014, most of the popular CRM products were linked to business intelligence systems and communication software to improve corporate communication and end-users' experience.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The leading trend is to replace standardized CRM solutions with industry-specific ones, or to make them customizable enough to meet the needs of every business.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In November 2016, Forrester released a report where it "identified the nine most significant CRM suites from eight prominent vendors".
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Strategic CRM concentrates upon the development of a customer-centric business culture.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The focus of a business on being customer-centric (in design and implementation of their CRM strategy) will translate into an improved CLV.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The primary goal of CRM systems is integration and automation of sales, marketing, and customer support.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, these systems typically have a dashboard that gives an overall view of the three functions on a single customer view, a single page for each customer that a company may have.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The dashboard may provide client information, past sales, previous marketing efforts, and more, summarizing all of the relationships between the customer and the firm.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Operational CRM is made up of three main components: sales force automation, marketing automation, and service automation.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The role of analytical CRM systems is to analyze customer data collected through multiple sources and present it so that business managers can make more informed decisions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Analytical CRM systems use techniques such as data mining, correlation, and pattern recognition to analyze customer data.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These analytics help improve customer service by finding small problems which can be solved, perhaps by marketing to different parts of a consumer audience differently.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For example, through the analysis of a customer base's buying behavior, a company might see that this customer base has not been buying a lot of products recently.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] After reviewing their data, the company might think to market to this subset of consumers differently to best communicate how this company's products might benefit this group specifically.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The third primary aim of CRM systems is to incorporate external stakeholders such as suppliers, vendors, and distributors, and to share customer information across groups, departments, and organizations.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For example, feedback can be collected from technical support calls, which could help provide direction for marketing products and services to that particular customer in the future.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] A customer data platform (CDP) is a computer system used by marketing departments that assembles data about individual people from various sources into one database, with which other software systems can interact.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] As of February 2017, about twenty companies were selling such systems and revenue for them was around US$300 million.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] When building and managing customer relationships through marketing, firms might benefit from using a variety of tools to help organizational design, incentive schemes, customer structures, and more to optimize the reach of their marketing campaigns.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Through the acknowledgment of the distinct phases of CRM, businesses will be able to benefit from seeing the interaction of multiple relationships as connected transactions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The final factor of CRM highlights the importance of CRM through accounting for the profitability of customer relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] By studying the particular spending habits of customers, a firm may be able to dedicate different resources and amounts of attention to different types of consumers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems may also incorporate automation features to streamline repetitive tasks such as data entry, follow-ups, and customer segmentation.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Relational Intelligence, which is the awareness of the variety of relationships a customer can have with a firm and the ability of the firm to reinforce or change those connections, is an important component of the main phases of CRM.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies may be good at capturing demographic data, such as gender, age, income, and education, and connecting them with purchasing information to categorize customers into profitability tiers, but this is only a firm's industrial view of customer relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] A lack of relational intelligence is a sign that firms still see customers as resources that can be used for up-sell or cross-sell opportunities, rather than people looking for interesting and personalized interactions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Customer satisfaction has important implications for the economic performance of firms because it has the ability to increase customer loyalty and usage behavior and reduce customer complaints and the likelihood of customer defection.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The implementation of a CRM approach is likely to affect customer satisfaction and customer knowledge for a variety of different reasons.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Firstly, firms can customize their offerings for each customer.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] By accumulating information across customer interactions and processing this information to discover hidden patterns, CRM applications help firms customize their offerings to suit the individual tastes of their customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This customization enhances the perceived quality of products and services from a customer's viewpoint, and because the perceived quality is a determinant of customer satisfaction, it follows that CRM applications indirectly affect customer satisfaction.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM applications also enable firms to provide timely, accurate processing of customer orders and requests and the ongoing management of customer accounts.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For example, Piccoli and Applegate discuss how Wyndham uses IT tools to deliver a consistent service experience across its various properties to a customer.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Both an improved ability to customize and reduced variability of the consumption experience enhance perceived quality, which in turn positively affects customer satisfaction.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM applications also help firms manage customer relationships more effectively across the stages of relationship initiation, maintenance, and termination.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] With CRM systems, customers are served on the day-to-day process.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] With more reliable information, their demand for self-service from companies will decrease.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] If there is less need to interact with the company for different problems, then the customer satisfaction level is expected to increase.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These central benefits of CRM will be connected hypothetically to the three kinds of equity, which are relationship, value, and brand, and in the end to customer equity.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Eight benefits were recognized to provide value drivers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Enhanced sales force efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Improved customer service efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Individualized marketing messages are also called campaigns.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Connect customers and all channels on a single platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Research has found a 5% increase in customer retention boosts lifetime customer profits by 50% on average across multiple industries, as well as a boost of up to 90% within specific industries such as insurance.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies that have mastered customer relationship strategies have the most successful CRM programs.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For example, MBNA Europe has had a 75% annual profit growth since 1995.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The firm heavily invests in screening potential cardholders.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Once proper clients are identified, the firm retains 97% of its profitable customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] They implement CRM by marketing the right products to the right customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The firm's customers' card usage is 52% above the industry norm, and the average expenditure is 30% more per transaction.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Also 10% of their account holders ask for more information on cross-sale products.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Amazon has also seen successes through its customer proposition.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The firm implemented personal greetings, collaborative filtering, and more for the customer.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] They also used CRM training for the employees to see up to 80% of customers repeat.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] A customer profile is a detailed description of any particular classification of customer which is created to represent the typical users of a product or service.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Customer profiling is a method to understand your customers in terms of demographics, behaviour and lifestyle.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] It is used to help make customer-focused decisions without confusing the scope of the project with personal opinion.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Overall profiling is gathering information that sums up consumption habits so far and projects them into the future so that they can be grouped for marketing and advertising purposes.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Customer or consumer profiles are the essences of the data that is collected alongside core data (name, address, company) and processed through customer analytics methods, essentially a type of profiling.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The three basic methods of customer profiling are the psychographic approach, the consumer typology approach, and the consumer characteristics approach.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These customer profiling methods help you design your business around who your customers are and help you make better customer-centered decisions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Consultants hold that it is important for companies to establish strong CRM systems to improve their relational intelligence.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] According to this argument, a company must recognize that people have many different types of relationships with different brands.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] One research study analyzed relationships between consumers in China, Germany, Spain, and the United States, with over 200 brands in 11 industries including airlines, cars, and media.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This information is valuable as it provides demographic, behavioral, and value-based customer segmentation.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These types of relationships can be both positive and negative.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Some customers view themselves as friends of the brands, while others as enemies, and some are mixed with a love-hate relationship with the brand.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Some relationships are distant, intimate, or anything in between.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Managers must understand the different reasons for the types of relationships, and provide the customer with what they are looking for.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies can collect this information by using surveys, interviews, and more, with current customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies must also improve the relational intelligence of their CRM systems.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies store and receive huge amounts of data through emails, online chat sessions, phone calls, and more.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many companies do not properly make use of this great amount of data, however.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] All of these are signs of what types of relationships the customer wants with the firm, and therefore companies may consider investing more time and effort in building out their relational intelligence.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies can use data mining technologies and web searches to understand relational signals.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Social media such as social networking sites, blogs, and forums can also be used to collect and analyze information.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Understanding the customer and capturing this data allows companies to convert customers' signals into information and knowledge that the firm can use to understand a potential customer's desired relations with a brand.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many firms have also implemented training programs to teach employees how to recognize and create strong customer-brand relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Other employees have also been trained in social psychology and the social sciences to help bolster customer relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Customer service representatives must be trained to value customer relationships and trained to understand existing customer profiles.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Even the finance and legal departments should understand how to manage and build relationships with customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Contact centre CRM providers are popular for small and mid-market businesses.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These systems codify the interactions between the company and customers by using analytics and key performance indicators to give the users information on where to focus their marketing and customer service.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This allows agents to have access to a caller's history to provide personalized customer communication.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The intention is to maximize average revenue per user, decrease churn rate and decrease idle and unproductive contact with the customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Growing in popularity is the idea of gamifying, or using game design elements and principles in a non-game environment, such as customer service settings.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The gamification of customer service environments includes providing elements found in games, like rewards and bonus points, to customer service representatives as a method of feedback for a job well done.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Gamification tools can motivate agents by tapping into their desire for rewards, recognition, achievements, and competition.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Contact-center automation, CCA, the practice of having an integrated system that coordinates contacts between an organization and the public, is designed to reduce the repetitive and tedious parts of a contact center agent's job.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Automation prevents this by having pre-recorded audio messages that help customers solve their problems.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For example, an automated contact center may be able to re-route a customer through a series of commands asking him or her to select a certain number to speak with a particular contact center agent who specializes in the field in which the customer has a question.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Software tools can also integrate with the agent's desktop tools to handle customer questions and requests.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This also saves time on behalf of the employees.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Social CRM involves the use of social media and technology to engage and learn from consumers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Because the public, especially young people, are increasingly using social networking sites, companies use these sites to draw attention to their products, services and brands, with the aim of building up customer relationships to increase demand.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] With the increase in the use of social media platforms, integrating CRM with the help of social media can potentially be a quicker and more cost-friendly process.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Some CRM systems integrate social media sites like Twitter, LinkedIn, and Facebook to track and communicate with customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] These customers also share their own opinions and experiences with a company's products and services, giving these firms more insight.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, these firms can both share their own views and track the opinions of their customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Enterprise feedback management software platforms combine internal survey data with trends identified through social media to allow businesses to make more accurate decisions on which products to supply.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems can also include technologies that create geographic marketing campaigns.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The systems take in information based on a customer's physical location and sometimes integrates it with popular location-based GPS applications.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] It can be used for networking or contact management as well to help increase sales based on location.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Despite the general notion that CRM systems were created for customer-centric businesses, they can also be applied to B2B environments to streamline and improve customer management conditions.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] For the best level of CRM operation in a B2B environment, the software must be personalized and delivered at individual levels.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The main differences between business-to-consumer (B2C) and business-to-business CRM systems concern aspects like sizing of contact databases and length of relationships.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In the Gartner CRM Summit 2010 challenges like "system tries to capture data from social networking traffic like Twitter, handles Facebook page addresses or other online social networking sites" were discussed and solutions were provided that would help in bringing more clientele.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The era of the "social customer" refers to the use of social media by customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Some CRM systems are equipped with mobile capabilities, making information accessible to remote sales staff.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many CRM vendors offer subscription-based web tools (cloud computing) and SaaS.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Salesforce.com was the first company to provide enterprise applications through a web browser, and has maintained its leadership position.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Over the years, the number of SaaS providers has grown with CRM being the leading category for 2024.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Traditional providers moved into the cloud-based market via acquisitions of smaller providers: Oracle purchased RightNow in October 2011, and Taleo and Eloqua in 2012; SAP acquired SuccessFactors in December 2011 and NetSuite acquired Verenia in 2022.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Sales forces also play an important role in CRM, as maximizing sales effectiveness and increasing sales productivity is a driving force behind the adoption of CRM software.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Some of the top CRM trends identified in 2021 include focusing on customer service automation such as chatbots, hyper-personalization based on customer data and insights, and the use of unified CRM systems.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM vendors support sales productivity with different products, such as tools that measure the effectiveness of ads that appear in 3D video games.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Pharmaceutical companies were some of the first investors in sales force automation (SFA) and some are on their third- or fourth-generation implementations.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] However, until recently, the deployments did not extend beyond SFA—limiting their scope and interest to Gartner analysts.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Another related development is vendor relationship management (VRM), which provide tools and services that allow customers to manage their individual relationship with vendors.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] VRM development has grown out of efforts by ProjectVRM at Harvard's Berkman Center for Internet & Society and Identity Commons' Internet Identity Workshops, as well as by a growing number of startups and established companies.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] VRM was the subject of a cover story in the May 2010 issue of *CRM* Magazine.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Another trend worth noting is the rise of Customer Success as a discipline within companies.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] More and more companies establish Customer Success teams as separate from the traditional Sales team and task them with managing existing customer relations.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This trend fuels demand for additional capabilities for a more holistic understanding of customer health, which is a limitation for many existing vendors in the space.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] As a result, a growing number of new entrants enter the market while existing vendors add capabilities in this area to their suites.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In 2017, artificial intelligence and predictive analytics were identified as the newest trends in CRM.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Companies face large challenges when trying to implement CRM systems.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Consumer companies frequently manage their customer relationships haphazardly and unprofitably.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] They may not effectively or adequately use their connections with their customers, due to misunderstandings or misinterpretations of a CRM system's analysis.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Clients may be treated like an exchange party, rather than a unique individual, due to, occasionally, a lack of a bridge between the CRM data and the CRM analysis output.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many studies show that customers are frequently frustrated by a company's inability to meet their relationship expectations, and on the other side, companies do not always know how to translate the data they have gained from CRM software into a feasible action plan.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In 2003, a Gartner report estimated that more than $2 billion had been spent on software that was not being used.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] According to CSO Insights, less than 40 percent of 1,275 participating companies had end-user adoption rates above 90 percent.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Many corporations only use CRM systems on a partial or fragmented basis.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] In a 2007 survey from the UK, four-fifths of senior executives reported that their biggest challenge is getting their staff to use the systems they had installed.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Forty-three percent of respondents said they use less than half the functionality of their existing systems.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] However, market research regarding consumers' preferences may increase the adoption of CRM among developing countries' consumers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Collection of customer data such as personally identifiable information must strictly obey customer privacy laws, which often requires extra expenditures on legal support.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Part of the paradox with CRM stems from the challenge of determining exactly what CRM is and what it can do for a company.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The CRM paradox, also referred to as the "dark side of CRM", may entail favoritism and differential treatment of some customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] This can happen because a business prioritizes customers who are more profitable, more relationship-orientated or tend to have increased loyalty to the company.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Although focusing on such customers by itself is not a bad thing, it can leave other customers feeling left out and alienated, potentially decreasing profits.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] CRM technologies can easily become ineffective if there is no proper management, and they are not implemented correctly.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] The data sets must also be connected, distributed, and organized properly so that the users can access the information that they need quickly and easily.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Research studies also show that customers are increasingly becoming dissatisfied with contact center experiences due to lags and wait times.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] They also request and demand multiple channels of communication with a company, and these channels must transfer information seamlessly.
[src:salesforce-platform/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, it is increasingly important for companies to deliver a cross-channel customer experience that can be both consistent as well as reliable.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Hosted applications: From the 1990s traditional application service providers (ASPs) hosted (then-existing) applications on behalf of their customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Depending on the limitation of the underlying application, ASPs were forced to host applications on separate machines (if multiple instances of the applications could not be executed in the same physical machine) or as separate processes.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a more mature architecture which enables a similar service with lower operational cost.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Web applications: Popular consumer-oriented web applications (such as Hotmail) developed with a single application instance serving all customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a natural evolution from this model, offering additional customization to groups of users within (say) the same client organization.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] In a multitenancy environment, multiple customers share the same application, running on the same operating system, on the same hardware, with the same data-storage mechanism.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] The distinction between the customers is achieved during application design, so that customers do not share or see each other's data.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] This contrasts with virtualization, where components are transformed so that each customer application appears to run on a separate virtual machine.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] This is attractive because redesigning an application for multitenancy can be costly, particularly for software vendors who also continue to offer an on-premises single-tenant version of their product and would otherwise have to maintain two distinct products.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] When applications are repackaged as virtual appliances, the same appliance image can be deployed in ISV-hosted, on-premises, or trusted-third-party locations, and migrated from one deployment site to another over time.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenancy allows for cost savings over and above the basic economies of scale achievable from consolidating IT resources into a single operation.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] An application instance usually incurs a certain amount of memory and processing overhead which can be substantial when multiplied by many customers, especially if the customers are small.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenancy reduces this overhead by spreading it over many customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Further cost savings may come from licensing costs of the underlying software (such as operating systems and database management systems).
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Put crudely, if you can run everything on a single software instance, you only have to buy one software license.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] In addition, development of multitenant systems is more complex, and security testing is more stringent because multiple customers' data is being commingled.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Because of the additional customization complexity and the need to maintain per-tenant metadata, multitenant applications require a larger development effort.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Considerations such as how tenant data is partitioned, how per-tenant schema extensions are stored, and how shared resources are isolated must be taken into account.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenancy simplifies the release management process.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] In a traditional release management process, packages containing code and database changes are distributed to client desktop and/or server machines; in the single-instance case, this would be one server machine per customer.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] These packages then have to be installed on each individual machine.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] With the multitenant model, the package typically only needs to be installed on a single server.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] This greatly simplifies the release management process, and the scale is no longer dependent on the number of customers.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] At the same time, multitenancy increases the risks and impacts inherent in applying a new release version.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] As there is a single software instance serving multiple tenants, an update on this instance may cause downtime for all tenants even if the update is requested and useful for only one tenant.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Also, some bugs and issues resulted from applying the new release could manifest in other tenants' personalized view of the application.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Because of possible downtime, the moment of applying the release may be restricted depending on time usage schedule of more than one tenant.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] A central design decision in a multitenant application is how each tenant's data is isolated within shared storage.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] When tenants share compute, storage, or network resources, a single tenant generating disproportionate load can degrade performance for others, a condition known as the "noisy neighbor" problem.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Mitigations include per-tenant rate limiting, resource quotas, and isolating high-demand tenants onto dedicated resources.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] According to Marc Brooker, in a multi tenant architecture, unrelated and uncorrelated workloads should be grouped together.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] That's because mixing different workloads, with different needs and patterns, hide the patterns of each workload.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Grouping workloads reduces the peak-to-average ratio of the overall system; individual workloads can utilize more resources during peak times without significantly increasing the overall cost structure of the system and subsequently helps you to achieve more cost efficiency.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Note that multiple workloads from the same application, customer or industry, tend to behave as a single workload.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are typically required to provide a high degree of customization to support each target organization's needs.
[src:salesforce-platform/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are expected to provide adequate security, robustness and performance between multiple tenants which is provided by the layers below the application in case of multi-instance applications.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:salesforce-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
